+.Op Fl v
+.Sh DESCRIPTION
+The
+.Nm
+utility manages desired and runtime state for cells and named volumes in one
+CLI surface.
+Desired state is stored in manifests under
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr .
+Runtime state is rendered under
+.Pa /var/cellmgr .
+The
+.Cm apply
+command reconciles desired state into runtime state.
+.Pp
+Within each runtime cell root,
+.Pa /.overlay
+is mounted as the writable layer.
+Common writable paths
+.Pq Pa /etc , Pa /var , Pa /tmp , Pa /home , Pa /root , Pa /usr/pkg
+resolve through that overlay.
+.Pp
+Storage backups are stored under
+.Pa /var/backups/cellmgr/volumes
+and
+.Pa /var/backups/cellmgr/overlays
+as
+.Pa <name>_YYYYmmddHHMMSS.tar.gz .
+.Pp
+Cell runtime and merged views include an
+.Dq age
+field derived from kernel cell creation time.
+For direct CLI human-readable output,
+.Dq age
+is rendered using compact units (for example
+.Dq 42s ,
+.Dq 7m12s ,
+or
+.Dq 3h05m )
+while TSV output and IPC-routed output emit raw seconds for client-side rendering.
+.Pp
+Optional create-time rlimits for supervise workloads can be configured per cell
+using
+.Cm --rlimit-nofile ,
+.Cm --rlimit-as ,
+and
+.Cm --rlimit-core
+.Pq or the corresponding manifest variables .
+When unset, supervise processes keep the system default behavior
+.Pq commonly unlimited on host defaults .
+.Pp
+Cell and volume names follow
+.Dq [A-Za-z0-9._-] .
+.Pp
+Read commands support unified output flags:
+.Bl -tag -width "--view merged|desired|runtime"
+.It Cm --view Ar merged|desired|runtime
+Select projection scope for
+.Cm list ,
+.Cm show ,
+and
+.Cm fields .
+Default is
+.Dq merged .
+.It Fl o Ar fields
+Select fields as comma-separated tokens in output order.
+.It Fl T
+Emit stable TSV output.
+.It Fl H
+Omit the TSV header line
+.Pq requires Fl T .
+.El
+.Pp
+Mutating commands support
+.Cm --scope
+to control the effect domain:
+.Bl -tag -width "--scope desired|runtime|both"
+.It Cm --scope Ar desired
+Change desired state only.
+.It Cm --scope Ar runtime
+Change runtime state only.
+.It Cm --scope Ar both
+Apply both desired and runtime effects.
+.El
+.Sh COMMANDS
+.Bl -tag -width "cell remove name --scope desired|runtime|both"
+.It Cm system Cm bootstrap Op Cm --xbase
+Prepare system prerequisites, fetch sets, and build shared base layer.
+.It Cm ipc Cm serve Op Cm --stdio
+Start the stdio message endpoint for long-lived clients.
+The command reads framed requests from standard input and writes framed
+responses to standard output.
+This command does not require root by itself, but dispatched subcommands keep
+their existing privilege requirements.
+.It Cm cell Cm list Op Ar output-options
+List cells from the selected
+.Cm --view .
+Default output is a human-readable table.
+.It Cm cell Cm show Ar name Op Ar output-options
+Show one cell row from the selected
+.Cm --view .
+.It Cm cell Cm fields Op Ar output-options
+List supported field names for the selected
+.Cm --view .
+.It Cm cell Cm create Ar name Op Ar cell-options
+Create desired cell manifests.
+With
+.Cm --scope both ,
+run targeted convergence for the created cell.
+At runtime render time, host
+.Pa /etc/resolv.conf
+and
+.Pa /etc/localtime
+are copied into the cell
+.Pa /etc
+overlay to seed DNS and timezone defaults.
+.It Cm cell Cm set Ar name Op Ar cell-options
+Update desired cell manifest values.
+With
+.Cm --scope both ,
+run targeted convergence for the updated cell.
+.It Cm cell Cm remove Ar name|--all|--orphans Op Ar remove-options
+Remove desired and/or runtime cell state according to
+.Cm --scope .
+Destructive
+.Cm --all
+and
+.Cm --orphans
+operations require interactive confirmation or
+.Cm --yes .
+.It Cm cell Cm start|stop|restart Ar name|--all Op Cm --scope Ar runtime|both
+Perform runtime lifecycle actions.
+With
+.Cm --scope both
+for
+.Cm start
+and
+.Cm stop ,
+desired autostart is updated to match intent.
+.It Cm cell Cm shell Ar name
+Open an interactive shell in a running cell.
+.It Cm cell Cm edit Ar name Op Cm --target Ar cell|apply Op Cm --cell Op Cm --apply
+Open one declarative cell file in an editor.
+By default, edits
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.cell .
+Use
+.Cm --target apply
+or
+.Cm --apply
+to edit
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.apply .
+.It Cm cell Cm backup Cm create Ar name
+Create a compressed backup archive of a cell runtime overlay.
+The cell must be stopped.
+.It Cm cell Cm backup Cm list Ar name Op Fl T Op Fl H
+List backup archives for one cell overlay, newest first.
+.It Cm cell Cm backup Cm restore Ar name Op Cm --from Ar archive.tar.gz Op Cm --latest Op Cm --manifest Op Cm --yes
+Restore runtime overlay content from a backup archive.
+The cell must be stopped.
+With
+.Cm --manifest ,
+restore associated
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.cell
+and
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.apply
+snapshots when available.
+.It Cm cell Cm backup Cm delete Ar name Op Cm --from Ar archive.tar.gz Op Cm --latest Op Cm --yes
+Delete one backup archive for a cell overlay.
+.It Cm cell Cm plan Cm run Ar name Op Cm --file Ar plan.apply Op Cm --ephemeral
+Run one declarative apply plan for a cell.
+Without
+.Cm --file ,
+the default
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.apply
+is used.
+.It Cm volume Cm list|show|fields Op Ar output-options
+Read volume state with the same
+.Cm --view/-o/-T/-H
+contract used by cell read commands.
+.It Cm volume Cm create|set Ar name Op Fl m Ar mode Op Cm --scope Ar desired|both
+Create or update desired volume manifest values.
+With
+.Cm --scope both ,
+materialize runtime volume path from desired state.
+.It Cm volume Cm edit Ar name
+Open
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.volume
+in an editor.
+.It Cm volume Cm remove Ar name|--all|--orphans Op Ar remove-options
+Remove desired and/or runtime volume state according to
+.Cm --scope .
+.It Cm volume Cm backup Cm create Ar name
+Create a compressed backup archive of the runtime volume directory.
+.It Cm volume Cm backup Cm list Ar name Op Fl T Op Fl H
+List backup archives for one volume, newest first.
+.It Cm volume Cm backup Cm restore Ar name Op Cm --from Ar archive.tar.gz Op Cm --latest Op Cm --manifest Op Cm --yes
+Restore runtime volume content from a backup archive.
+Without
+.Cm --from ,
+the latest matching backup is selected automatically.
+With
+.Cm --manifest ,
+restore the associated
+.Pa /etc/cellmgr/<name>.volume
+snapshot when available.
+.It Cm volume Cm backup Cm delete Ar name Op Cm --from Ar archive.tar.gz Op Cm --latest Op Cm --yes
+Delete one backup archive for a volume.
+Without
+.Cm --from ,
+the latest matching backup is selected automatically.
+.It Cm system Cm reset Op Cm --scope Ar desired|runtime|both Op Cm --cells Op Cm --volumes Op Cm --yes
+Reset selected resource groups by chaining destructive
+.Cm --all
+operations for cells and/or volumes.
+When neither
+.Cm --cells
+nor
+.Cm --volumes
+is specified, both are reset.
+.It Cm apply Op Cm --all | Ar name ... Op Cm --dry-run Op Cm --reapply Op Cm --restart-changed Op Cm --silent Op Fl v
+Reconcile desired state to runtime state.
+With
+.Cm --dry-run ,
+print the plan only and return exit status 2 when changes would be required.
+.El
+.Sh IPC PROTOCOL
+The
+.Cm ipc serve --stdio
+endpoint uses framed messages on stdin/stdout.
+Each message starts with an ASCII header line:
+.Bd -literal -offset indent
+M 1 <TYPE> <ID> <P1> <P2> <P3> <LEN>\n
+.Ed
+followed by exactly
+.Ar LEN
+payload bytes.
+.Pp
+Supported message types are:
+.Bl -tag -width "CALL"
+.It HELLO
+Handshake frame.
+.It CALL
+Execute a CLI request.
+.Ar P1
+is mode (0=capture, 1=interactive tty),
+.Ar P2
+is argv count.
+.Ar P3
+is an environment override flag (0=none, 1=payload starts with key/value lines).
+Payload is newline-delimited text entries.
+When
+.Ar P3
+is 1, the payload starts with
+.Dq env_key
+and
+.Dq env_value
+lines followed by argv entries.
+Arguments and optional environment values must not contain literal newline
+bytes.
+.It RET
+Command response.
+.Ar P1
+is exit status,
+.Ar P2
+and
+.Ar P3
+are stdout/stderr byte counts.
+Payload is stdout bytes followed by stderr bytes.
+.It ERR
+Protocol/server error.
+.Ar P1
+is an error code.
+.It PING , PONG , BYE
+Keepalive and shutdown control frames.
+.El
+.Pp
+Maximum accepted payload size is 64 MiB.
+.Sh EXIT STATUS
+.Bl -tag -width Ds
+.It 0
+Success.
+.It 1
+Failure.
+.It 2
+Only for
+.Cm apply --dry-run :
+changes would be required.
+.El
+.Sh FILES
+.Bl -tag -width /usr/share/examples/cellmgr/cellmgr.conf.sample
+.It Pa /etc/cellmgr.conf
+Global defaults.
+.It Pa /etc/cellmgr
+Desired manifests
+.Pq Pa *.cell , Pa *.apply , Pa *.volume .
+.It Pa /var/cellmgr/cells
+Rendered runtime cell tree.
+.It Pa /var/cellmgr/cells/*/overlay
+Per-cell writable runtime overlay, mounted in-cell at
+.Pa /.overlay .
+.It Pa /var/cellmgr/volumes
+Runtime volume directories.
+.It Pa /var/backups/cellmgr/volumes
+Volume backup archives.
+.It Pa /var/backups/cellmgr/overlays
+Overlay backup archives.
+.It Pa /usr/share/examples/cellmgr/cellmgr.conf.sample
+Sample configuration.
+.El
+.Sh SEE ALSO
+.Xr cellctl 8 ,
+.Xr secmodel_cell 9
+.Sh HISTORY
+The
+.Nm
+utility first appeared in an unofficial patch set for
+.Nx
+11.0 .
+.Sh AUTHORS
+.An Matthias Petermann Aq Mt mp@petermann-digital.de
diff --git a/usr.sbin/cellmgr/examples/README b/usr.sbin/cellmgr/examples/README
new file mode 100644
index 000000000000..03598087f4a3
--- /dev/null
+++ b/usr.sbin/cellmgr/examples/README
@@ -0,0 +1,151 @@
+# cellmgr examples (unified CLI)
+
+`cellmgr` uses a flat desired-state directory:
+
+- `/etc/cellmgr/<name>.cell`
+- `/etc/cellmgr/<name>.apply`
+- `/etc/cellmgr/<name>.volume`
+
+Runtime state is rendered under:
+
+- `/var/cellmgr/cells/<name>/...`
+- `/var/cellmgr/volumes/<name>`
+
+
+## Core workflow
+
+1) Bootstrap system prerequisites:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr system bootstrap
+```
+
+Use `--xbase` when your workloads require files from `xbase.tar.xz`:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr system bootstrap --xbase
+```
+
+2) Create desired manifests:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr cell create demo-edge-httpd \
+  --autostart YES \
+  --profile medium \
+  --reserved-ports 8080 \
+  --rlimit-nofile 4096 \
+  --rlimit-as 1073741824 \
+  --rlimit-core 0 \
+  --cmd '/usr/libexec/httpd -I 8080 -X -f -s /var/www/demo-edge-httpd'
+```
+
+3) Edit generated `*.cell` / `*.apply` files as needed.
+
+4) Reconcile desired to runtime:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr apply --dry-run --all
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr apply --all
+```
+
+
+## Unified read API
+
+Human table:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr cell list --view merged
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr volume list --view merged
+```
+
+Machine TSV:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr cell list --view merged -T -H -o name,cid,refs,procs,running,manifest
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr volume list --view merged -T
+```
+
+
+## Desired vs runtime scope
+
+Mutating commands accept `--scope`:
+
+- `desired` (default for create/set/remove)
+- `runtime`
+- `both`
+
+Examples:
+
+```sh
+# desired only
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr cell set demo-edge-httpd --autostart NO --scope desired
+
+# runtime only
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr cell stop demo-edge-httpd --scope runtime
+
+# desired + runtime
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr cell start demo-edge-httpd --scope both
+```
+
+
+## Volume examples
+
+Create desired volume and materialize runtime path immediately:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr volume create demo-webroot -m 0755 --scope both
+```
+
+Attach in a cell manifest:
+
+```sh
+CELL_VOLUME_MOUNTS="demo-webroot:/var/www/demo:rw"
+```
+
+`<volume>:<target>[:ro|rw]` is required per entry.
+
+
+## Example stacks in this directory
+
+The following example trees are shipped:
+
+- `httpd/`
+- `mantisbt/`
+- `api-gateway/`
+- `blue-green/`
+- `php-api/`
+- `luanti/`
+- `forgejo/`
+
+Copy example manifests into `/etc/cellmgr` and run:
+
+```sh
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr apply --dry-run --all
+/usr/sbin/cellmgr apply --all
+```
+
+
+## Apply plan directives
+
+`<name>.apply` supports:
+
+- `PKG <package>`
+- `EXEC <command>`
+- `DIR <path> [mode=0755] [owner=user] [group=group]`
+- `LINE <path> | <text>`
+- `SYMLINK <target> <linkpath>`
+- `FILE_BEGIN <path> [mode=0644] [owner=user] [group=group]`
+- `FILE_END`
+- `PATCH_BEGIN <path> [strip=0]`
+- `PATCH_END`
+
+Before executing each plan, `cellmgr` runs `certctl rehash` inside the target
+cell and exports `PKG_PATH` for package operations.
+
+
+## Operational notes
+
+- Keep `/etc/cellmgr` under version control.
+- Prefer one supervised service per cell.
+- `--all` / `--orphans` destructive removals require confirmation or `--yes`.
+- `CELL_DEPENDS_ON` defines reconcile order and rejects dependency cycles.
